The first virtual operator will reach the Czech Republic already this year.
Maybe
Perhaps the mobile phone market in the Czech Republic is mature enough and our operators offer almost all services as their partners in Western Europe.
Here, however, something is missing – a virtual operator that obliges traditional ones to lower the price.
Maybe it won't be long.
The fact that Czech operators belong to the most expensive ones in Europe has already written on Mobil.cz many times.
In the end it has also confirmed ČTU, which has noted that the price of SMS is higher from us than in the rest of the Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the area of regulating roaming tariffs, perhaps a paradoxical situation will be created - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS will cost less from abroad than at home.
How can prices in the Czech Republic remain so high against Europe?
The answer is simple, lacks the competition that would really want to start the fight.
It may sound absurd, even here we have three mobile networks and cover highly over 100 %.
Instead mobile telephony operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this sense, the head of the Czech Telecommunications Council (ČTú) is often emphasized, Pavel Dvořák, who in the past stated that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It may be true that the traditional operator with his own network no longer has many possibilities. (Moreover, it may be difficult to find other frequencies.)
But there is still another possibility - the virtual operator.
The entry into the market of virtual operators has led to a significant decrease in prices, to which traditional operators would have to react.
At the same time before the entry of sharks like Tesko Mobile and Virgin Mobile into the market, similar voices were echoed in Britain as we did.
However, it has been shown that the place for such operators is there and that can really be successful.
Finally, we must not go too far for examples.
In February of this year we informed you of the arrival of the Virtual Operator Mobilking in Poland.
In only half a year this operator managed to conquer more than 100 thousand customers and become the fifth largest local operator.
At the same time behind Mobilking is the Penta financial group to which in the Czech Republic belongs among the other U:phone.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility of focusing on a much more concrete group-breeding.
In order to actually function, that is, many fewer customers than a traditional operator.
They do not go behind, i.e., relatively high costs for the creation, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
Thus in the world virtual operators usually present themselves at low cost, offer calls and SMS at low price, which is often in balance with the offer of the most restricted services
For example Tesco Mobile in Britain offers SMS that costs as much as half as its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can be a pretty good move even bet on a group-tweet not recently.
This operator aims to specifically say about men.
"The real men choose Mobilking operator that they like and you can trust," says David Seibertz CEO Mobile Entertainment Company that produces this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether we can also assert a similar concept as in Poland.
The press spokesman for Vodafone Miroslav Čepický doubts: "The Czech market is relatively small for a fragmented approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, from the point of view of services is relatively full."
In the Czech Republic no possibility, say mobile network operators
But it seems almost certain that if there is ever an operator in the Czech Republic it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic negotiations do not have much to expect.
Mobilking's ignition will take place in other countries in our area," he said in a telephone dialogue for Mobile.cz Jana Studničková, the press spokesman for the Penta financial group.
It has thus indirectly confirmed that current operators in the Czech Republic are not particularly in favour of this view.
Rather, they try to do everything because no competing potential is created.
For a while it has not hidden its interest in the start of a virtual operator, the GTS Novera group that would like to take another step to become a real competitor of Telefónika O2 in the field of business customers.
"We have a great interest in offering our customers not only fixed services but also mobile telecommunications.
And first it's better.
We have repeatedly negotiated on this possibility with all the Czech mobile network operators.
We have already been able to progress in negotiations with some of them," says the spokesman of the Pavel Kaidl Group.
So maybe better times will come.
Unofficial information shows that the first virtual operator will have to have it by the end of the year.
But for now around its creation there is an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At this moment we do not believe that in the Czech market there is room for the creation of a fully-fledged virtual operator.
The Czech market, unlike other markets, is very specific.
So far no subject with a complex and serious project has addressed us," he mentioned in his statement to Mobil.cz Vlastimil Sršeň from the Telefónika O2 press section.
The specificity of the Czech market also applies to other operators.
The press spokesman for T-Mobil Martina Kemrová adds in a rare agreement with the O2 declaration: "For now we have not noticed any vital and beneficial commercial project for both, on which it is possible to continue to build".
And he adds: "On the T-Mobile network a virtual operator will hardly appear by the end of the year.
At this moment we have already had to have a concrete agreement on the table, so that it could be considered at the horizon."
Vodafone concentrates its attention rather than reaching its 3G licence requests.
Adds Miroslav Čepický: "We are open to the negotiations of potential virtual operators, especially in the context of spending and infrastructure sharing.
Let us consider this, from a customer's point of view, the most productive.
Vodafone's main strategy in this field is to find a partner to build a common network for fast mobile internet."
Competent authorities -with complicating operators
The attitude of mobile telephone operators can easily be understood, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would lead to lower prices and thus to lower profit.
Why then facilitate the rise of such a competitor?
Troubles around the creation U:phone testify that when operators hold to something they know how to remedy on the same side.
Perhaps the great pressure was pressing towards ČTU in the period of creation of U:phone to the company of T-Mobile.
This testifies to public access information from the ČTú web pages.
But now U:fon serves as a topic for which to not accept the virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová observed: "The competition environment of the mobile phone market has been little boosted by the entry of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
With regard to the type of mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that another competitor’s entry would place on him and above all on his high claims services.”
However, the attitude of mobile telephony operators is quite surprising to the complete disinterest of Czech regulators.
It is not only the attitude of the ČTU that unfortunately in the Czech Republic - unlike Britain and other developed countries - has no competence to interfere in economic competition.
It belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (UOHS).
This, however, in relation to the whole problem has taken its typical position.
"The entry of the virtual operator into the mobile phone market would be possible after the conclusion of the contract of the rental of the required infrastructure between mobile operator and virtual operator had been realized.
No such contract has been concluded so far because the offer of potential buyers has probably not been sufficiently interesting for traditional operators," said Kristián Chalupa, from the external relations section ÚOHS, in the answer to our question.
Such a statement by the representatives of the operators might not be surprising.
On the other hand, the office must defend the interests of consumers and, above all, take care of the fact that no one takes advantage of its position on the market, it is more than a delicate business.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "Outside where virtual operators commonly operate, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to lower prices for mobile telephone services."
But of course the pressure on the correct functioning of the market environment and lower prices do not belong to the interests of UOHS.
It is truly shocking in the whole situation is the almost exciting harmony of these three operators resulting from their reactions.
The question as to whether this is really just a coincidence is a matter of itself.
Similarly, the same price of petrol for all petrol is undoubtedly the result of coincidence and competitive struggle.
"The section has not found any signs of anti-competitive behaviour regarding this fact and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
No operator has a dominant position, so he does not have a corresponding greater responsibility for his behaviour on the market.
The necessary tools for opening the mobile network market for virtual operators may also be missing the telecommunication regulator," said Chalupa in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many controversial points .
There is, of course, an analysis of the relevant markets developed by ČTU, according to which telecommunications are from the point of view of economic competition the only market.
On a market like this, of course, no Czech operator has a dominant position.
But some legal experts offer another approach - for the creation of a virtual operator it is always necessary the agreement of the network operator.
And the mobile operator has - ultimately logically – the monopoly of his network.
So for a certain portion it must be dominant by force.
But even if we do not admit this argument, for UOHS it should be a minimum warning that three mobile operators do so strangely similar.
At the same time, complaints from stakeholders (including the so-called GTS Novera company) show that during negotiations with all operators encounter very similar obstacles.
Downloading responsibility to ČTU in telecommunications is a fairly frequent trick with which ÚOHS is kept out of the whole matter.
We have already found this in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, it was not possible to promote the expansion of ČTU's rights in the field of economic competition in telecommunications until the recently approved telecommunications law was updated, despite the fact that many experts expected to improve the situation.
This is what UOHS representatives need to know more than well, but perhaps their interests are elsewhere.
You can do it when no one looks
While we are unaware of this, the operation of these pseudo-virtual operators remains, some of which even exist in the Czech mobile networks.
These are companies that publish their own price lists of mobile telephone services, but are only partially public.
These are usually companies that deal with multilevel marketing.
So for example Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and a number of others offer their mobile phone services.
The prices of these companies usually reach only the pre-determined persons.
Magic is in the fact that the company against the operator is a classic business customer, who orders a large amount of SIM card.
As an important customer then receives special price offers (and more).
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile telephony operators prohibit such a presale.
"If the cases referred to above were presented, of which we will be interested, it could be a breach of contractual conditions, and it could result in the conclusion of cooperation with that company," replied the question in question Martina Kemrová.
But it is quite unlikely that such an activity would not reach the ears of those responsible for mobile telephony operators.
Especially in the cases of the three companies mentioned, thousands of customers may be involved.
No operator defends himself at the same time from such an attitude.
From the activities of these companies, that is, they derive a non-indiferent profit and at the same time - unlike the real virtual operators - they are not harmed in any way by their official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns about possible problems: "The law allows similar speculations, however only a negligible percentage of customers uses the services of these companies.
These must also accept that the SIM card on their phone is not registered on their behalf, so they cannot fully dispose of it as the usual customers of mobile phone operators "
But this should be a little weird about Čtú.
In addition, another issue is open for UOHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes in front of such an attitude, why are they blocking the creation of the virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that UOHS has strong enough rights to expose similar activities and if he does not want to, he must not be satisfied with the explanation of the operators who have no idea of all that and that their commercial conditions prohibit it.
When we're no longer expensive
As has already been said several times in the text, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile phone market has led to a significant decrease in prices for services.
At the same time, in virtually all countries where operators were born, traditional operators tried to prevent their creation.
The arguments they used were almost identical - too small market, at the limit too saturate, problems with the quality of services etc.
But in the developed countries in these cases, the defence regulators have intervened not of mobile operators but of their customers.
Both with the formal measures both with the non-formal pressure, then came to the creation of the first virtual operator and to him came up with others.
Unfortunately, Czech regulators throw from one another all the time as a boiling potato.
For our experience, we can't get rid of the feeling that the lack of clarity in these cases makes them more than comfortable.
But we don't throw away the sponge.
If backstage information is right and the virtual operator will appear to us very soon, the Czech mobile phone market will be moved back.
If one of the operators consented to the creation of a virtual mobile operator only rarely UOHS could remain unimpeded by the refusal (discrimination) of the others concerned.
And we may stop calling at higher prices than the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best one
Listen to the four new versions of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek on the occasion of the Czech State's Day of Recognition presented in a solemn way the new recordings of the national anthem "Kde kasov m a.j."
The new anthem was recorded by the orchestra of the National Theatre under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available – solo with male or female voice, chorus step and instrumental edition.
The song is under the direction of Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
The authors of the anthem revisions are Otakar Jeremiaš and Jaroslav Krček.
On the iHNed.cz site you can listen to all four versions.
Bělohlávek considers the Czech national song one of the most beautiful hymns.
Earlier he told the radio "Český rozhlas" that he chose specifically to sing the variants alone, the singers with the most representative young voices, which are expressive and popular.
"From the beginning I tried to take care that both and also the choir, have the clear dictionary, that the text is well understood, that they are in harmony," he said.
Then the national anthem will celebrate next year the 175th anniversary.
The song "Kde kasov m a.j." was played for the first time in 1834 on the stage of the Stavovskéh divadlo in the original work Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetán Tyl accompanied by music by František Škroupa.
He bought popularity and people spontaneously made it his own.
The first stanza of the song after the foundation of Czechoslovakia in 1918 then became the natural part of the national anthem.
One of the seven national symbols remained even after the birth of the Czech Republic.
