Alcoholic relapse drivers will have to install "alcohol"
The Ministry of the Interior requires drivers with three administrative penalties for excessive blood alcohol, to install in their car the system that prevents driving the vehicle in a state of drunkenness or if it does not blow up the device.
The measure was announced last June and is already included in the annual report of the Attorney-General's Office, according to which it will be a one-year pilot project.
The purpose of this project is to reintegrate the driver, since this will have to attend a road rehabilitation course.
This initiative, in addition to the Public Prosecutor's Office for Road Safety, will participate in the Directorate-General for Traffic (DGT) and the Fondazione Istituto Tecnologico per la Seguridad dell'Automobile (FITSA).
According to statistics, between 30% and 75% of reported motorists reported more than once per driving in a state of drunkenness then return to driving the car.
Alcohol will avoid it, because it is a system connected to the vehicle that measures the alcohol rate in the breathed air and prevents the driver from setting up the car if the driver does not blow, or when a higher alcohol concentration is detected than the permitted one.
The cost is higher than 1000 euros and would be borne by the sanctioned person.
In this regard, a study conducted in the United States in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with such devices allow for a reduction of up to 65% of the infringements committed during the first year of introduction.
And in Spain it is estimated that it could save the lives of 115 people a year.
The measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to stop these behaviors before they become criminal offences.
And to facilitate its development, since legal reform can be carried out on a regular basis, and, no doubt, the reform necessary for the criminal procedure would require an organic law.
However, the device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial solution, although it has already been introduced experimentally in some industrial and public vehicles.
Just tomorrow, the Congress of Deputies will vote on an initiative by the PSOE which proposes to install this system on school buses, as has already been done in France.
