Talking in the sleep
Some children talk during the night.
I am not referring to those who wake up very excited to tell us something that happened to them the day before, but to those children who speak while sleeping.
The first time it happens, at most it takes a scare, but actually it doesn't matter very much.
This is a benign alteration of the sleep defined dreamword.
It manifests with a certain frequency, especially in children and adolescents.
Certainly, most of you told me you had spoken in your sleep.
This phenomenon can occur in a very sporadic way (once in life, for example associated with a high fever episode) or with greater regularity (every day, once a week, once a month ...), the day after the child does not remember anything.
There is no single reason to explain this phenomenon.
Sometimes there are episodes related to other sleep disorders such as nightmares, night fears, nocturnal enuresis (do pee in bed), or sleepwalking, but not necessarily so.
As mentioned above, it can be associated with very high fever stages, stress situations or overcrowding.
In any case, it is still a little studied phenomenon.
Even the intensity with which it appears to be extremely variable.
It may happen that the person speaks with a very quiet tone of voice, with loose words, almost in a whisper or that the opposite happens (screams, screams, long speeches ...).
In cases where the event is particularly intense, it would be appropriate to observe the child and possibly consult a specialist to see if there is any question that is generating an abnormal state of anxiety as a way out of the situation.
We said that this is a benign alteration therefore there is no treatment unless it is associated with other sleep disorders that can be treated (for example, if coupled with insomnia or stress situation).
What can be done instead is to consider a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child too much before he goes to sleep.
Offer quiet games and avoid TV programs or series that arouse fear or suggest violence.
With very nervous children for which it is difficult to relax, relaxing techniques can be used to help them acquire some inner calm.
This will allow the child to sleep more quietly.
Once the sleepwalkers appear to try to keep calm.
Remember that they are harmless for the child and that the next day he will remember nothing of what has happened.
Useful advice
Don't wake him.
It is useless, because he is not aware of what is happening, and you will interrupt his sleep.
Although he's talking, he's sleeping and so he's resting.
Remember that if you appear very distressed and episodes have a certain frequency, you should consult a doctor or check where your child is experiencing such anxiety.
If you understand what it says (which is not the most common situation), do not fall into temptation to interrogate him for information.
You won't get anything, because he's asleep and so unconscious to organize his thinking.
In addition, you are able to hear what he says but not see what he is dreaming to say, so you must pay very much attention to the interpretation of the information and the conclusions to which they might lead.
Never tell the child that you could ask questions during the night to know his secrets.
Not even for jokes.
Something like this causes enormous anxiety.
