The meeting - The blood is safe again
Hema-Québec celebrated yesterday the tenth anniversary of its foundation, and its president, Dr. FrancineDécary, had every reason to rejoice because Hema-Québec became one of the safest and most effective blood providers in the world.
And above all, it has regained the confidence of the public, seriously shaken by the scandal of infected blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As we know, the national reserves of blood managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were infected by the acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C in the 1980s.
In the face of such a drama and the protests of the population, the Government of Canada conducted a public investigation in February 1994, led by Judge Horace Krever, which aimed to highlight the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to disseminate recommendations to prevent the recurrence of such a disaster.
While Judge Krever was delaying writing a report, some provinces have set up a committee with the aim of designing a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, this mandate was carried out by the Gélineau Committee.
Following the Gélineau et Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Hema-Québec to provide Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society (Canadian Blood Society) for all other provinces and two territories.
In 1998, when Héma-Québec began its activities, just 38% of people said they still believed in the donation system in Quebec, Dr. Décary recalled.
The situation was deadly.
Thanks to continued efforts to improve the safety of blood samples and field research over the next few years, we have regained the confidence of the public," he explained before proudly saying that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of Quebec's population now had confidence in Hema-Québec.
However, Dr. Décary is convinced that "trust is something extremely fragile".
Since its establishment on 28 September 1998, Hema-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At the time, there were numerous cases in Europe of the human variant of the mad cow, a new manifestation of Creutzfeldt-Jakob’s disease, told by those who had been in the presidency since 1998, the year of the foundation.
"And we didn't know at all whether that disease could be transmitted through infected blood.
Therefore, one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélinau reports has been based on one of the main recommendations, according to which, when one has doubts and could achieve a serious disease, in this case the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease that manifests itself with a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, exclusion measures are taken.
In April 1999, the blood of those who had spent more than a month in the United Kingdom since 1980 was refused.
Now, for some years, it has been shown that this disease is undoubtedly transmitted by infected blood.
This episode has shown us that it has made sense to apply the precautionary principle."
In 1999 a much more efficient technique for detecting HIV appeared on the market: the tests of nucleic acid (TAN) that allow the presence of the virus and not of antibodies against the virus directly in the blood of donors, on which the tests used so far were based.
The TANs have allowed to reduce the window period, since the person contracted the disease to the one where the first viruses can be identified in the blood thanks to our techniques, explains the specialist.
That period could be reduced to less than one week.
The risk of ignoring the presence of infected donors and therefore not being able to identify them is thus greatly diminished.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS with a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
"In other words, this means that 12 million blood samples will need to be distributed before someone gets infected with the HIV virus.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400 000 and 500 000 blood samples every year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of HIV is found transmitted with a transfusion.
I believe that you can feel calm today when you receive or prescribe a blood transfusion to recover your health, says the head of the management of Hema-Québec.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen will emerge in the system.
Not later than a year ago the Chikungunya virus appeared on Réunion Island, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted in blood by an insect.
We need to be constantly vigilant," continues Dr. Décary before stressing that, in addition to having secure resources, Hema-Québec must also provide sufficient resources.
"Necessity increases as the population grows older.
Since treatment against cancer is more aggressive, patients often need a supply of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing population also has consequences on the number of donors who on average constitute only 3% of Quebec's inhabitants acceptable as donors."
However, all healthy people who have reached the age of 18 years and meet the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of the people who offer themselves as donors are not accepted, because they are affected by AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled to a country where the latter is spread, they will be refused for a period of one year.
"With this 3% we can maintain an inventory capable of responding to the needs of hospitals.
The cases of shortage are very rare.
But it is necessary to renew the members of this group of donors as they grow old and cannot make donations anymore.
Now it is difficult to convince people to donate blood, but especially to hold them back and encourage them to become regular donors.
Nowadays life is so frenetic that it is hardly an hour to donate blood," says desolate Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of 297 million dollars, Hema-Québec distributes not only blood samples, but also human tissues, including bone transplants, eyeball heart valves and skin that is used almost exclusively for severe burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being deposited with the Hema-Québec that manages the only public bank of umbilical cord blood in Quebec.
In the umbilical cord, which was once considered a biomedical waste, abundant blood rich in stem cells that can help cure serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the entry into the bank of our thousandth blood sample of cordon and we plan to take more than a thousand each year.
You should start to propose them for transplants at the beginning of next year," said Dr. Décary who describes this practice of taking cordon blood as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed that they can't have access to you," because Héma-Québec has no means to propose this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
