Because for Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate would be to bring ruin to anyone who dares to support a position contrary to his own.
Little matter the outcome of the process, the writers and the editor of the book Canada Nero will have to spend a large amount of money in order to organize their defense and fight, to decidedly learnt weapons, against an army of lawyers financed by virtually no fund pockets of the mining company.
On the other hand, in these struggles with odd weapons, the tactic is often to ruin the defendant in order to impose a consensual regulation that invades the opposition as well as scare everyone else to decide again on the matter.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it is first of all the public opinion that she should have presented her own view of the facts.
Contrary to what happens in many countries where Barrick Gold works, in Canada the debates usually take place with the exchange of views rather than with manganello blows.
It would therefore be sufficient for the company to open its books, its documents, and to establish a real debate, through newspapers, media, publications and the financing of teams of independent researchers who could have shed light on the matter.
But Barrick Gold doesn't seem to have too much confidence in public opinion and rejects petitions and letters in support of the authors of Black Canada.
Perhaps Garver could explain how he can ask for a "public" debate when his contempt for that same audience is quite obvious?
In the world of the vice-president, it seems that this word indicates only profusely paid lawyers and not the whole of Canadians; here is a rather narrow view of the concept.
In a democratic system, even the denigrators have the right to speak.
What Barrack Gold does not understand – or does not want to understand – is that the public who supports the authors and editors of Canada Nero does it first because it rejects the brutal means taken by the mining company.
This audience is ready to listen to Barrick and judge, but on the basis of civil exchanges of opinion, and not in the view of what many perceive as a kind of embalming (requiring the "public debate", Barrick Gold has just given the authors of Canada Nero an ultimatum urging them to suspend the use of that word...)
