For 2007, Inail data confirm that the white deaths were approximately 1,200.
Figures that testify to the severity of a phenomenon that remains one of the main causes of death and causes almost double the deaths from homicides.
To draw the attention of institutions, social forces and media on this dramatic issue, today the Anmil celebrates in all the provinces of Italy the 58th National Day for the Victims of Accidents at Work, institutionalized on the second Sunday of October.
"The worrying data disseminated by the Anmil and the same tragic events of these days confirm how crucial both the question of prevention at work," said President Giorgio Napolitano, in the message sent to the President of the Anmil, National Association Mutilated and Disabled of Work, Pietro Mercandelli.
The Head of State expresses his "live appreciation for the ongoing association commitment to prevention at work, protection of unfortunate workers, assistance to victims' families and awareness of public opinion".
"It has, of course, raised a 'sufficient' outrage, sincerely shared, in the face of tragedies that, due to their size, provoke the cries of the media and the involvement of public opinion but the daily reality re-proposes dramatic cases, even repetitions in their dynamics."
Napolitan does not hide that "there is undoubtedly also a problem of resources: it is crucial to invest in training and information.
Particularly significant are the many initiatives promoted in school for a more direct awareness of young people facing the world of work.
It is important to keep an eye on the phenomenon, not to delay in alarming its social gravity, to apply and improve legislative rules.
For his part, the President of the Gianfranco Fini Chamber stressed "as the phenomenon of white deaths constitutes an absolute social emergency, which offends the conscience of each one of us and imposes on all institutions a firm commitment to bring you to an urgent end".
"Data on accidents at work seem to indicate a slight positive development, but this does not remove that the number of white deaths is nevertheless impressive," noted the president of Anmil Pietro Mercandelli.
"We would not, in fact, want this "low-down trend" to be less attention, because it is precisely when attention slows down that tragedy explodes.
"We believe that at general level there is still too little to tackle the phenomenon of accidents and the contrast can be exercised through multiple actions.
In our opinion - it has emphasized Mercandelli - more controls and inspections, but also a stronger intervention on the training of workers, and this from the school world".
"It serves a further effort - it has added - as far as communication and public awareness are concerned.
But, above all, there is a need for greater sense of responsibility on the part of employers for a phenomenon that represents a social emergency."
Mercandelli then denounced "the progressive deterioration of the levels of compensation provided for the victims of work" and "the last care system towards which the system is moving in recent years".
"The objective is therefore to return the insurance guarantee to the worker - he added - because the fate of those who are unfortunate should not depend on spontaneousisms or occasionally extension arranged by the legislator."
Mp3 readers under charge, put the audience at risk
Listening to high-volume music for a prolonged period of time using portable musical devices such as Mp3 readers can cause permanent hearing damage.
This is what the European Commission says, which in a statement published in Brussels quotes the opinion of the Scientific Committee on Emerging and Recently Identified Health Risks (Cssseri) of the EU, published today.
"From this scientific opinion - we read in the note - it turns out that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to music with portable musical devices weekly for more than an hour a day while holding the high volume device risk a permanent loss of hearing ability."
"I am concerned that such a large number of young people who frequently use portable musical devices and mobile phones at high sound levels can unconsciously damage their hearing in an irreparable way," says Meglena Kuneva.
"From scientific findings - the EU responsible continues - there is a clear risk and we must react quickly.
What matters most, we need to raise consumers' awareness and make this information public.
We must also review existing control systems, in the light of this scientific opinion, in order to ensure that they are fully effective and keep pace with the new technology."
Brussels had asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the widespread use of portable musical equipment and the increase in the number of young people exposed to noise from them.
"Scientists - concludes the EU executive - confirm that there is cause for concern and the European Commission will now examine with the Member States and stakeholders what measures could possibly be taken to better protect children and adolescents from noise exposure from portable musical equipment and similar equipment."
At present, there is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable musical equipment to 100 dB, but concerns about hearing damage can result from excessive exposure to such noise sources.
It is possible to limit these damage by resorting to solutions such as reduction of levels and duration of noise exposure.
In its opinion, the EU Scientific Committee notes that users of portable musical equipment listen to music (more than 89 decibels) for only 5 hours per week exceed the current limits on maximum noise at work.
Those who listen to music in these conditions for longer periods risk a permanent loss of hearing capacity after a period of 5 years.
This would cover 5-10% of users of these devices and their number can be quantified between 2.5 million and 10 million people in the EU.
