The elites in danger
The phenomenon had already manifested itself a few days ago with the vote of the House of Representatives against the 700 billion-dollar rescue plan launched by the White House: a significant part of Americans was, and is, more interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the economy.
It gives us a confirmation of yesterday's New York Times informing us that the ongoing crisis is breaking down the Republican Party, increasingly divided between its old East Coast, moderate, favourable to federal institutions and business community, and its new soul, instead, conservative, hostile to "those in Washington" and to the world of finance, strong especially in the Central and South States.
The soul, by the way, which became prepotently alive with the vote I said at the beginning.
However, this is only an example of the changes, of the major changes, which the ongoing economic earthquake may pre-announce or already lets notice: not only in the United States but throughout the West and perhaps even here only.
Both in the US and in Europe the crisis seems to be a accelerator of incubation phenomena for long and in the new climate they are solidifying and finally coming to light.
The first of these phenomena is the updating, the extraordinary relaunching, of the dual category State-Sovereignity in relation to a kind of renationalisation of the economy.
The crisis, in fact, is a crisis of banking-financial institutions which have, yes, close ties with the outside world, but which at first see the budgets of people and families living in one country, in one State.
This immediately creates a political problem for those who govern it: that is, how to respond to the difficulties and protests of those people and families who, among other things, are also an electorate.
In short, the crisis appears economically global but politically it is almost exclusively national.
Political internationalism seems largely out of play or has little to say: the clear proof is given by the European Union which divides as usual between the different interests and between the different state strategies cannot decide any common political line.
And so it is from the government of every single state that everyone expects interventions, rescue and recovery plans, new rules, and above all the provision of funds: since when it comes to tights it is only the States that own economic resources, the mass of financial resources able to try to put things back in sixth place.
They also have the necessary means and legitimacy to use them: two resources of immeasurable value, in certain circumstances, of which no market and no international organisation will ever be able to provide to a similar extent.
This new emphasis that the crisis puts on the institutional-national element is, moreover, in perfect harmony with the increasing importance that the most recent developments in the economy tend to attribute to a factor that is very closely related to that element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, in fact, while we were convinced that we were now entering the realm of the network, of increasingly sophisticated technology, of immaterials, while we were convinced that globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we realized from one point that our future will have to do more with those very little material things that are water, crops, oil.
All things that, look a little bit, can certainly be transported from one place to another on earth but are nevertheless absolutely connected to a confined space, to a territory.
As for those who are sovereign, they certainly have several more cards than those who are not, to those who have the misfortune of living in a place without crops, without oil and without water.
I come to the second news, however, which predicts a fracture.
Those who say Territory, State, Government, inevitably say Politics, and therefore Leadership.
In this regard, the economic crisis seems to produce two convergent phenomena.
On the one hand, the awareness of the objective need for authoritative leadership, the demand of someone who knows how to take the situation in hand.
On the other hand, a wave of discretion for existing leadership, economic species, turned out to be so inadequate and full of shadow zones.
And together something even deeper and in a certain disquieting sense: a discreet, insufficient, an image of inadequacy, a sense of distance, which tends to involve the entire ruling class in a growing number of Western countries.
That is to say, it seems that in many sectors of the population, the belief that before their actions are the same ideas of the social elites so far at the height, their way of feeling and being, their culture in the overall meaning of the term, that they have made their own time and that they are increasingly alien to the views of the majority.
The demand for leadership, in short, feeds underground a branch but powerful movement of dellegitimization of the ruling classes and traditional political arrangements, which manifests itself in the sudden "revolts" election or in sudden developments of the collective moods of recent and recent times, from the conservative rise in Austria-Baviera to the collapse of the workers' consensus in Britain, to the rebellion of the American congressmen against Bush (and perhaps also the victory of the right in Italy has something to do).
We have the impression that traditional elites, their parties, their programs, but also their rites, their newspapers, their accredited intellectuals, their formats would say someone, make it increasingly difficult to understand, and therefore to represent, what is not taking shape today in the deep layers of Western societies and that the economic crisis revives, increases, stirs up potentially in dismusement.
In view of all this speaking of a "mass rebellion" on the agenda would be quite frankly exaggerated.
But keeping your eyes open is certainly not at all.
