Goodbye old cinema Paradise, cities erase historic rooms
Historical cinemas close in favour of the Multiplex.
"A city without cinematographic halls is a blind city, it's like an eyeless face."
The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornator effectively photographes what is happening in the large Italian urban centers but also in the cities of the province.
The process of marginalization of cinemas, with the birth in the periphery of large multisales and the consequent death by constipation of monosals in the central areas of the cities, is one of those events that appear to us inelutable and incontrovertible but also has all the characteristics of a real cultural crime.
Disappearing are often historical places and loads of memory," it is as if less a friend, an acquaintance with whom we shared a piece of street and many emotions," observes the director of New Cinema Paradiso, the film that lasts twenty years in Tornatore the Oscar Prize and the Grand Prix of the Cannes jury, and which told the poetry of a province hall and nostalgia for a way of living the film lost perhaps forever.
The figures provided by Anec, the main association of the exhibitors, speak clearly: in the last five years 316 traditional cinemas have been closed, and to pay for the major show are mainly the rooms in the main cities: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closures is Emilia-Romagna with 82 cinemas, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
And to demonstrate that the first responsible for their disappearance is the advent of multiplex, these are the three Italian regions that have recorded the largest number of new multi-sala cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 both in Tuscany and in Emilia-Romagna.
"The Italian exercise has developed irrationally" observes Paolo Protti, president of Anec, "it is useful to build new structures but it would need to ensure the survival of those already existing, because when a city hall closes, not all its visitors are willing to move into multiplex.
Not to mention the lack of funding for the fund for the workers: the government's debt is about 10 million euros.
It is shameful, from an ethical and moral point of view, that the Government does not comply with existing laws.
In order to support the sector, it would be worth between 16 and 18 million euros per year".
Interesting is the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that, concerned about the closures, has decided to run the shelters with the signing of a protocol between Town and Anec, the first such in Italy, to protect and promote the cinemas monosala both in the historical centre and in the outskirts.
Among the rules provided are tax facilitation measures for managers and benefits to the public in terms of mobility: spectators can enter the restricted traffic area and will have special rates for stopping and parking.
